    <h1>Returns</h1><div id="preamble">
<div class="sectionbody">
<div class="paragraph">
<p><strong>Item » Edit item » Tab: Statistics</strong>→ Statistic: Returns*<strong>*</strong></p>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>**== Returns</p>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>This statistic shows the monetary amounts of <strong>returns</strong> according to the selected <strong>time span</strong> and the <strong>reason for return</strong>. As an alternative to selecting a certain predefined time span, you can also choose an individual <strong>start</strong> and <strong>end date</strong>. Default setting for the <strong>time span</strong>: the <strong>last 10 days</strong>.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div><div class="sect1">
<h2 id="_details_about_the_statistic">1. Details about the statistic</h2>
<div class="sectionbody">
<div class="paragraph">
<p>The <strong>number of sales orders</strong> and the corresponding <strong>revenue in Euro</strong> will be displayed for the selected <strong>time span</strong>. Furthermore, the returns are sorted according to the <strong>reason for return</strong>. If a particular type of sales order did not occur during the selected time span, then this type of sales order will not be displayed. The name of the <strong>reason for return</strong> and the corresponding <strong>amount in Euro</strong> will be displayed as <strong>information in a mouseover</strong> (see image 1). In this statistic you can see, e.g. how many <strong>returns</strong> were made during a particular time period and how much of your <strong>revenue</strong> was affected. Furthermore, you can see how the <strong>number</strong> of returns and the corresponding <strong>amounts</strong> are divided up among the different <strong>reasons for returns</strong>. This can help you monitor your refunds.</p>
</div>
<div class="admonitionblock warning">
<table>
<tbody><tr>
<td class="icon">
<i class="fa icon-warning" title="Warning"></i>
</td>
<td class="content">
<div class="title"><strong>Item bundles</strong></div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>The <strong>number of returned items from item bundles</strong> will be analyzed. However, the corresponding <span class="underline">revenue will not</span>. <strong>Item bundles</strong> do not have any data available within the <strong>Statistics</strong> tab.</p>
</div>
</td>
</tr>
</tbody></table>
</div>
<div class="admonitionblock note">
<table>
<tbody><tr>
<td class="icon">
<i class="fa icon-note" title="Note"></i>
</td>
<td class="content">
<div class="title"><strong>Show details (mouseover)</strong></div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>Point your <strong>cursor</strong> at one of the elements in the statistic in order to see <strong>details</strong> about that particular element.</p>
</div>
</td>
</tr>
</tbody></table>
</div>
<div class="admonitionblock tip">
<table>
<tbody><tr>
<td class="icon">
<i class="fa icon-tip" title="Tip"></i>
</td>
<td class="content">
<div class="title">Tip</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>In image 1, you can see that <strong>1</strong> return was made because an item was <strong>broken</strong>. Furthermore, you can see that this return has a total <strong>amount</strong> of <strong>393.49 Euro</strong>.</p>
</div>
</td>
</tr>
</tbody></table>
</div>
